etymologies: late 16th century. From classical Latin praecursus anticipation, forestalling from praecurs-, past participial stem of praecurrere to run in front of, precede + -tus, suffix forming verbal nouns

definitions: A heralding or foreshadowing of future events.

notes.text: In modern use frequently with allusion to "curse".

etymologies: late 19th century; earliest use found in Alfred Tennyson (1809–1892), poet. From classical Latin praecurs-, past participial stem of praecurrere to run in front of, to precede

definitions: To be a precursor to; to run or occur before; to herald, portend.
